      "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/validation/no-comparator",
      "type": "ValidationResult",
      "name": "Primary hemolysis QoI validation — CFD vs. bench (CPB operating envelope)",
      "description": "Normalized index of hemolysis (NIH) and relative hemolysis index (RH) were computed for all five flow-speed combinations (2 L/min–3500 RPM through 6 L/min–5000 RPM) using the power-law Giersiepen-Wurzinger damage accumulation model integrated along Lagrangian particle trajectories. Predicted NIH values ranged from 0.0021 to 0.0078 mg/dL, consistent with published CFD benchmarks for centrifugal geometries. The worst-case operating point (3 L/min, 4500 RPM) yielded RH = 0.83, satisfying the RH < 1 acceptance criterion. Agreement between CFD and laboratory measurements was characterized as good across the operating envelope. No systematic bias was identified in the pressure-flow characteristic curves (maximum deviation 4.2 % at peak flow). The validation narrative references the NIST VAD hemolysis reference dataset as corroborating evidence for model fidelity, citing close agreement in shear-stress exposure distributions and cumulative damage integrals. The dataset is described as broadly applicable to centrifugal blood-contacting devices and is presented without qualification regarding differences in operating pressure head, inlet hematocrit, or anticoagulation protocol relative to the CPB COU.",
      "quantitativeMetric": "RH = 0.83 at worst-case operating point; NIH RMSE = 0.0009 mg/dL across 5 operating points",
      "passFail": "pass"
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/validation/secondary-vad-comparator",
      "type": "ValidationResult",
      "name": "Secondary validation — shear-stress distribution against NIST VAD reference dataset",
      "description": "Volume-averaged and surface-area-averaged wall shear stress distributions predicted by the CFD model were compared against the NIST VAD hemolysis reference dataset (NIST TN 2094, continuous-flow LVAD at 5 L/min, 8000 RPM, mean arterial pressure 85 mmHg). The NIST dataset was selected because it employs the same FDA generic impeller geometry and uses an identical power-law hemolysis model, ensuring numerical method comparability. Predicted shear-stress histograms showed good agreement (Kolmogorov-Smirnov statistic D = 0.07, p = 0.31), supporting the conclusion that the CFD solver accurately captures the fluid mechanical environment relevant to red blood cell damage. The comparison is presented as validation evidence for the CPB COU without noting that the NIST reference conditions (continuous-flow VAD at 8000 RPM, systemic pressure head ~85 mmHg, hematocrit 40 %) differ materially from CPB operating conditions (2–6 L/min, 3500–5000 RPM, venous return pressure head ~200–400 mmHg, hematocrit 28–32 % due to hemodilution). The elevated rotational speed and pressure head in the VAD reference case produce substantially higher shear-stress magnitudes and longer fluid residence times, meaning the damage accumulation integral from the NIST dataset is not directly transferable to the lower-speed CPB envelope. This mismatch is not examined in the validation narrative.",
      "quantitativeMetric": "KS statistic D = 0.07 vs. NIST TN 2094 VAD reference; wall shear stress mean deviation 6.1 %",
      "passFail": "pass",
      "comparedAgainst": "https://uofa.net/synth/data/nist-vad-hemolysis-reference-dataset"
    }
